Money Stuff =0A The Fannie Mae and Freddie Mac saga has been going on for, =
depending how you =0Acount, 16 years, or perhaps many decades. There are st=
rong feel =0A=0A=0A <> =0A =0A<https://sli.bloomberg.com/click=3Fs=3D825881=
&stpe=3Ddefault&li=3D12249185&m=3D21d6dea82d6b16615cf44233be620525&p=3D0108=
2025>=0A=0A=0A=0AThe GSE trade=0A=0AThe Fannie Mae and Freddie Mac saga has=
 been going on for, depending how you =0Acount, 16 years, or perhaps many d=
ecades. There are strong feelings and a lot =0Aof lore. It=E2=80=99sback <>=
 in the news <> now, and I thought it might be nice to =0Astart with the ba=
sics.=0A=0AIn the US, as a matter of policy for many decades now, the feder=
al government =0Awants it to be relatively easy to buy a house. Most people=
 do not have enough =0Amoney to buy a house, so this policy mostly means th=
at the government wants =0Asomeone to lend buyers the money on generous ter=
ms. [1]  <> In practice, =0A=E2=80=9Cgenerous terms=E2=80=9D means somethin=
g like =E2=80=9Ca 30-year fixed-rate mortgage with an =0Ainterest rate not =
that much higher than Treasury bond rates.=E2=80=9D=0A=0AThere are various =
