=0A =0A<https://sli.bloomberg.com/click=3Fs=3D868432&stpe=3Ddefault&li=3D12=
249185&m=3D21d6dea82d6b16615cf44233be620525&p=3D01082025>=0A=0A =0A<https:/=
/sli.bloomberg.com/click=3Fs=3D868432&stpe=3Ddefault&li=3D12249185&m=3D21d6=
dea82d6b16615cf44233be620525&p=3D01082025>=0A=0AGreen accounting=0A=0AYou c=
ould imagine a world without generally accepted accounting principles. In =
=0Athis world, companies would report their financial results in whatever w=
ay =0Aseemed right to them. They=E2=80=99d add up all the money that came i=
n, throw in all =0Athe money that they think really should have come in, an=
d subtract all of the =0Aexpenses that they wanted to subtract. The result =
would be their =E2=80=9Cnet income.=E2=80=9D =0AIt would probably be high=
=3F Deep down every company thinks it=E2=80=99s doing great, and =0Amaking =
money is the main indication of doing great, and the companies will all =0A=
make the accounting choices that make them look good.=0A=0AAnd some of this=
 will be fraud, but most of it won=E2=80=99t be; most of it will be =0Acomp=
anies making good-faith choices that they think represent their financial =
=0Aposition accurately. But those choices will be biased by their optimism,=
 and by =0Ahow they run their business: They will mostly do deals that they=
 think are =0Agood, so they will account for those deals as profitable. [13=
]  <>=0A=0AAnd so you can see why GAAP exists: If every company is required=
 to use the =0Asame methods to prepare their financial reports, those finan=
cial reports will =0Abe comparable with each other. Some companies will mak=
e money; others will lose =0Amoney. Whereas if every company could use its =
own methods, every company would =0Amake money.=0A=0AActually you don=E2=80=
=99t need to do too much imagining here: Lots of US public =0Acompaniesdo r=
eport both GAAP net income and some other, non-GAAP income number =0A=E2=80=
=94 =E2=80=9Cadjusted EBITDA=E2=80=9D is the stereotypical name for it =E2=
=80=94 that tends to make them =0Alook better. (The stereotypical way to ca=
lculate adjusted EBITDA is to take =0Ayour negative net income for the quar=
ter and add things back to it until you =0Aget a positive number. [14]  <>)=
 Loosely speaking, it is almost true that every =0Acompany makes money, by =
its own standards, but some companies lose money, by =0AGAAP standards.=0A=
=0AStill this can only be so true. There is a lot of room for interpretatio=
n, but =0Anotinfinite room. At some level, either the money comes in or it =
doesn=E2=80=99t.=0A=0AMeanwhile companies increasingly disclose information=
 about environmental =0Asustainability and carbon emissions, and while ther=
e are a lot of =0Asustainability accounting standards at this point, we do =
seem to be much closer =0Ato the world without GAAP. And presumably every c=
ompany will think =E2=80=9Cwe are =0Adoing the right things for sustainabil=
ity, so our sustainability score is =0Apositive 100,=E2=80=9D or whatever, =
whereas if you just picked a single standard for =0Asustainability accounti=
ng some companies would be positive 100 and others would =0Abe negative 60.=
=0A=0AAnyway here=E2=80=99s a funny story about how the European Investment=
 Bank=E2=80=99s =0Aclimate-friendly loans make upeither 50% of its assets o=
r 1%, depending how you =0Acount <>:=0A=0AThe European Investment Bank fear=
s a =E2=80=9Creputational disaster=E2=80=9D this year if the =0AEU applies =
reporting rules that would shatter its climate-friendly credentials, =0Aacc=
ording to leaked internal correspondence.=0A=0AThe world=E2=80=99s biggest =
multilateral lender by assets has branded itself as =E2=80=9Cthe =0Aclimate=
 bank=E2=80=9D and from 2021 phased out all fossil fuel investments from it=
s =0Aloan book of more than =E2=82=AC500bn.=0A=0ABut in a confidential emai=
l to colleagues seen by the Financial Times, the =0AEIB=E2=80=99s head of o=
perations Jean-Christophe Laloux warned of a =E2=80=9Cmajor reputational =
=0Arisk=E2=80=9D to the bank from new EU sustainable reporting rules, which=
 this year =0Arequire a taxonomy classifying green investments.=0A=0AThe re=
porting reforms would force the bank to declare a =E2=80=9CGreen Asset Rati=
o=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94 =0Aan EU standard intended to show the proportion of a=
 bank=E2=80=99s assets considered =0Aclimate-friendly =E2=80=94 of =E2=80=
=9Caround 1 per cent=E2=80=9D, compared with its current =E2=80=9CClimate =
=0AAction ratio=E2=80=9D based on EIB-defined metrics that stands =E2=80=9C=
above 50 per cent=E2=80=9D.=0A=0ABoth sides have some points:=0A=0A[A lette=
r from development banks including the EIB] said that =E2=80=9Cthe way in =
=0Awhich the Green Asset Ratio is currently calculated penalises a whole ra=
nge of =0Aotherwise green investments, and will inadvertently, and paradoxi=
cally, =0Adiscourage the financing of climate action by policy-driven lende=
rs such as our =0Ainstitutions=E2=80=9D.=0A=0AThe commission has said that =
investments outside the EU are not included in =0Athe GAR because those bus=
inesses are not obliged to comply with the bloc=E2=80=99s =0Acorporate sust=
ainability rules. SMEs are also excluded.=0A=0AThe EIB, however, has been a=
ccused by campaign groups and current and former =0Aemployees of a lack of =
transparency in the way it operates and being overly =0Aconcerned about its=
 reputation at the expense of proper due diligence.=0A=0AAnd this is broadl=
y true of GAAP too: There are some imperfections in GAAP, =0Asome places wh=
ere you could argue that it doesn=E2=80=99t reflect economic reality, =0Aof=
ten because it is too conservative. But it is probably a good thing, in =0A=
general, to have a uniform accounting standard that sometimes embarrasses s=
ome =0Acompanies.=0A=0A=0A$5 wrench attack [15]  <> =0A=0AIf you do financi=
al crimes, the government might put you in prison and take =0Ayour money. I=
f your money is in a bank, the government can go to the bank with =0Aa cour=
t order saying it can take your money, and the bank will cheerfully hand =
=0Aover the money. (If it didn=E2=80=99t, it would get in trouble.) If your=
 money is in=0ABitcoin, though, there is no one for the government to go to=
 with a court =0Aorder: Your money is on a decentralized, censorship-resist=
ant blockchain, =0Aimpervious to the demands of the government. [16]  <>=0A=
=0AThis is somewhat less appealing than people sometimes think, though, bec=
ause =0Athe government can just come toyou with that court order, and say =
=E2=80=9Chand over =0Ayour Bitcoin or we=E2=80=99ll throw you back in jail.=
=E2=80=9D Only you have the private key, =0Abut the government has the jail=
. Bloomberg=E2=80=99sDavid Voreacos reports <>:=0A=0AAn early Bitcoin inve=
stor sentenced last month to two years in prison for tax =0Afraud related t=
o cryptocurrency sales has been ordered to disclose his secret =0Apass code=
s so US officials can unlock digital assets now valued at about $124 =0Amil=
lion.=0A=0AFrank Richard Ahlgren III, who owes the government about $1 mill=
ion in =0Arestitution from the criminal case, must hand over the pass codes=
 and identify =0Aany devices used to store them, along with disclosing all =
his cryptocurrency =0Aaccounts, US District Judge Robert Pitman ruled Monda=
y in federal court in =0AAustin, Texas. =E2=80=A6=0A=0AIn their request, pr=
osecutors said Ahlgren=E2=80=99s property =E2=80=9Ccannot be attached by =
=0Aordinary physical means.=E2=80=9D The government asked =E2=80=9Cnot only=
 to restrain any =0Avirtual currency by order of this court, but to obtain =
the private keys to =0Aenable it access so that it cannot be moved by other=
s. Should the private keys =0Abe lost or destroyed, the virtual currency is=
 irretrievable.=E2=80=9D=0A=0AA lot of technologies would work better and m=
ore simply and more pleasingly if =0Apeople did not have bodies that exist =
in physical reality, but we do.=0A=0A=0AThings happen=0A=0AFighting for a S=
hare of a $1 Trillion Market in Borneo=E2=80=99s Jungle <>. AI Startup =0AA=
nthropic <> Raising Funds Valuing It at $60 Billion. U.S. Expands RealPage =
=0APrice-Fixing Lawsuit <> to Include Six Big Landlords. Xi Jinping Muzzles=
 =0AChinese Economist Who Dared toDoubt GDP Numbers <>. JPMorgan Planning t=
o Bring =0AStaff to OfficeFive Days a Week <>. Zuckerberg Wears $900,000 Wa=
