 Pleads Guilty to =0AFraud Over =E2=80=98Unlimited=E2=80=99 Plan.=0A=0AIf y=
ou'd like to get Money Stuff in handy email form, right in your inbox, =0Ap=
leasesubscribe at this link <>. Or you can subscribe to Money Stuff and oth=
er =0Agreat Bloomberg newslettershere <>. Thanks!=0A=0A[1] There will be ma=
ny, many nuances that this column skips over, and this is =0Aone. As in stu=
dent loans, it is possible that making it easy to borrow money to =0Abuy a =
house pushes up the price of houses and thus ultimately makes it harder =0A=
to buy a house, but never mind!=0A=0A[2] You can imagine many more possibil=
ities. =E2=80=9CBank regulators put lower =0Acapital requirements on reside=
ntial mortgages,=E2=80=9D maybe, or =E2=80=9Cbank regulators =0Apunish bank=
s for not lending broadly enough,=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9Cbanks don=E2=80=99t =
have to pay taxes =0Aon mortgage interest received,=E2=80=9D or other thing=
s.=0A=0A[3] As we often  discuss <> around here, banks historically dominat=
ed lending, =0Abut increasingly they don=E2=80=99t. US mortgage lending =E2=
=80=94 in part *because* of the =0Aguarantee structure we'll discuss =E2=80=
=94 has long involved a lot of non-bank lenders.=0A=0A[4] Actually, the ori=
ginal approach in the 1930s was more of a blend of =0AApproaches 1 and 2: F=
annie Mae was originally a federal agency disbursing US =0Agovernment money=
 to banks to make mortgages. Butin the 1960s <>, =E2=80=9CFannie Mae =0Abec=
ame a private shareholder-owned corporation chartered by the U.S. Congress,=
=E2=80=9D =0Aapparently to get its (giant) operations off the government=E2=
=80=99s financial =0Astatements.=0A=0A[5] The FHFA was created in 2008 <> a=
nd succeeded the Office of Federal =0AHousing Enterprise Oversight <>, the =
previous regulator.=0A=0A[6] =E2=80=9CAll the Devils Are Here <>,=E2=80=9D =
Bethany McLean and Joe Nocera=E2=80=99s financial =0Acrisis book, covers th=
ese issues brilliantly.=0A=0A[7] I assume the reason for this was roughly t=
o make the Treasury facility =0Ajunior to all of the mortgage guarantees. B=
ut here is =E2=80=9CRatings Agencies: The =0AForgotten Constituency of Fina=
ncial Crisis Interventions <>,=E2=80=9D a clever recent =0Apaper by Ayo Geo=
rge and Steven Kelly at the Yale Program on Financial =0AStability, arguing=
 that a lot of bailouts are structured as preferred stock to =0Aappease rat=
ings agencies: A bailout in the form of additional lending could =0Amake th=
e problem worse as a matter of credit ratings. I=E2=80=99m not sure that wa=
s =0Arelevant here, though.=0A=0A[8] After they build up enough capital to =
meet regulatory requirements (which =0Ahas not happened yet), their payment=
 to the governmentwill be <> =E2=80=9Cthe lesser of =0A10% of the liquidati=
on preference of Treasury=E2=80=99s senior preferred stock, or the =0Aincre=
mental increase in the GSE=E2=80=99s net worth in the prior quarter.=E2=80=
=9D=0A=0A[9] These numbers =E2=80=94 the liquidation preferences of the pre=
ferred stocks =E2=80=94 =0Aadjust each quarter, as each increase in the ent=
erprises=E2=80=99 net worths is added =0Ato the amounts they owe. SoFannie =
says <>: =E2=80=9CThe aggregate liquidation =0Apreference of the senior pre=
ferred stock increased to $208.0 billion as of =0ASeptember 30, 2024 from $=
203.5 billion as of June 30, 2024, due to the $4.5 =0Abillion increase in o=
ur net worth in the second quarter of 2024. The aggregate =0Aliquidation pr=
eference of the senior preferred stock will further increase to =0A$212.0 b=
illion as of December 31, 2024, due to the $4.0 billion increase in our =0A=
net worth in the third quarter of 2024.=E2=80=9D AndFreddie <>: =E2=80=9CNe=
t worth was $56.4 =0Abillion as of September 30, 2024, up from $44.7 billio=
n as of September 30, =0A2023. The quarterly increases in net worth have be=
en, or will be, added to the =0Aaggregate liquidation preference of the sen=
ior preferred stock. The liquidation =0Apreference of the senior preferred =
stock was $125.9 billion on September 30, =0A2024, and will increase to $12=
9.0 billion on December 31, 2024 based on the =0Aincrease in net worth in 3=
Q 2024.=E2=80=9D=0A=0A[10] See pages 8-9 of Fannie=E2=80=99s most recent 10=
-K <> and page 5 of Freddie=E2=80=99s <>.=0A=0A[11] =E2=80=9CI do not belie=
ve the common stocks have much institutional or hedge fund =0Aownership tod=
ay except for Pershing Square so nearly all value recovered will =0Ago to t=
he government, taxpayers and small investors.=E2=80=9D=0A=0A[12] The regula=
tory capital framework for the enterprises includes a leverage =0Aratio of =
2.5% of adjusted total assets, meaning roughly 2.5% of mortgages =0Aguarant=
eed. (See page F-58 ofFannie=E2=80=99s 10-K <>.) There are also risk-based =
=0Acapital metrics that might, depending how you count, be more constrainin=
g.Ackman=0A <>: =E2=80=9CA 2.5% capital ratio is the same required for mort=
gage insurers who by =0Acomparison guarantee the first ~20% of losses on of=
ten riskier mortgages with =0Aless creditworthy borrowers, compared with th=
e GSEs=E2=80=99 guarantee which attaches =0Aat the senior-most <=3D80% of t=
he property=E2=80=99s mortgaged value. Mortgage insurers =0Atherefore typic=
ally incur 100% losses on a default whereas by comparison GSE =0Alosses on =
a default are minimal.=E2=80=9D=0A=0A[13] A classic in the financial sector=
 is: You think some asset is worth $100, =0Ait=E2=80=99s trading at $80, yo=
u buy it for $80. What is the value of that asset on =0Ayour financial stat=
ements=3F Do you have $20 of income the minute you buy it=3F The =0AGAAP an=
swer is mostly no, butthere are controversies <>.=0A=0A[14] This is very un=
fair, and for a while <> I liked to make fun <> of =E2=80=9Cpeople =0Aare w=
orried about non-GAAP accounting,=E2=80=9D but, you know, a little.=0A=0A[1=
5] This is a standard crypto term, from an xkcd <>.=0A=0A[16] Actually ther=
e=E2=80=99s a decent chance that your money is at a centralized =0Acrypto e=
xchange, and the government can go to the exchange with a court order, =0Aa=
nd the exchange will cheerfully hand over the money. (If it didn=E2=80=99t,=
 it would =0Aget in trouble.) But let=E2=80=99s assume it isn=E2=80=99t, th=
